            "header_by_html" : "<p><a href=\"https://unsplash.com/photos/vMfuMxaE31w\" target=\"_blank\">@simonrae</a> from Unsplash</p>",
            "header_by_markdown" : "[@simonrae](https://unsplash.com/photos/vMfuMxaE31w) from Unsplash",
            "header" : "article-header-5b2d9ffaae86ed7f92ac88b8.jpeg",
            "content_html" : "<h3 id=\"history\">History</h3>\n<p>The Harbour bridge is famous arc bridge in the middle of Sydney Bay. Still today it is on e of the main link between the CBD (South) and the North Shore. The bridge was opened in 1932, and it stay Today the tallest arch bridge ever build. As for most of the major construction of the beginning of the 20th century, this was a risky job. As a result 16 workers died during the construction, but \"only\" 2 from falling. On both side of the bridge 2 rock pylons had been erected. The pylons themselves has no structural purposes. They were added to the original design, to allay public concern about the structural integrity of the bridge.</p>\n<h3 id=\"activities\">Activities</h3>\n<p>Pedestrian can cross the bridge freely from both side of the bridge. This also offer a great view of the Opera house. Bicycle can also cross the bridge but only from the other side of the bridge next to the train rail. Since 1998 it is possible to climb the southern half of the bridge with the BridgeClimb company for $300. Because of an unsuccessful bid BridgeClimb won`t be able to operate as for October 2018.\nA huge park is also accessible under the Northern Pylons. This park offer a great view on all the South part of the city. Walking from the south side of the bridge you can also access Pyrmon. \nThe bridge is open all year long except for New year eve, indeed the bridge serve as the main launch station for the famous fireworks. As so the bridge close for few hours at that times.</p>",
