            "title" : "Carriagework",
            "header" : "article-header-5b2da414ae86ed7f92ac88d9.jpeg",
            "content_html" : "<h3 id=\"history\">History</h3>\n<p>Carriagework was build during the rail revolution in Australia as a railway workshops. They share the history of Australia’s rail  network during the bustling industrial time of the 19th century. Build between 1880 and 1889, they are considered as one of the best examples of railway workshop. And because of this history, the Carriageworks site is now heritage listed. But from 1973 productivity at the site declined, and eventually it closed in 1988.\nIn 2002 the NSW ministry for the arts completed the purchase of  the Carriage and Blacksmith Workshops. Soon after, a construction project on the site commenced under the name of Carriageworks.\nThe vision for Carriageworks was to became an artistic hub. This hub would be a place where creative work could be explored, developed, commissioned and presented.</p>\n<h3 id=\"ambiance\">Ambiance:</h3>\n<p>The first thing you notice when you arrive is the size of these workshops. half a dozen shed has been scraped down and now offer vast empty space where exhibitions takes place. But Carriagework is not only a museum. It is a host of many activities from a farmer's market to a cafe and much more. A bit like the Ground of Alexandria. And because the place has been renovated following it's original material. You can really enjoy a nineteenth century industrial atmosphere.  </p>\n<p>Carriageworks. Contemporary multi-arts program that engages artists &amp; audiences with ambitious, artist-led exhibitions &amp; performances. View What's On.\nPlace is important to the practice of art.</p>\n<p>Specialty roaster, The Little Marionette of Sydney’s Inner West, are  operating a pop up at Carriageworks offering a range of coffee, drinks  and snacks.\n Open daily, 9.30AM – 3PM</p>\n<h3 id=\"collection\">Collection:</h3>\n<p>Adding to the rich cultural atmosphere at Carriageworks are a number  of Resident Organisations, all working within the contemporary arts  sector: Contemporary Asian Australian Performance (CAAP), Erth, Force  Majeure, Performance Space, Sydney Chamber Opera, Moogahlin, Felix Media  and Marrugeku.\nOne of the main adantage of Carriagework is the size of its room. Which allow for really ambitious art installation, which could not been hosted anywhere else.</p>\n<h3 id=\"pricing\">Pricing:</h3>\n<h3 id=\"location\">Location:</h3>\n<p>open 10am – 6pm daily and open until late on performance nights.\nFor more information view Carriageworks Artistic Program.\nRedfern Station | 8 minute walk\nCarriageworks is housed in the old Eveleigh Rail Yards at Wilson  Street, located within the emerging Redfern Waterloo precinct, and has  been developed by the NSW State Government through Arts NSW.</p>\n<p>[address]() \n<a href=\"http://carriageworks.com.au\" target=\"_blank\">website</a></p>",
            "content_markdown" : "###History\nCarriagework was build during the rail revolution in Australia as a railway workshops. They share the history of Australia’s rail  network during the bustling industrial time of the 19th century. Build between 1880 and 1889, they are considered as one of the best examples of railway workshop. And because of this history, the Carriageworks site is now heritage listed. But from 1973 productivity at the site declined, and eventually it closed in 1988.\nIn 2002 the NSW ministry for the arts completed the purchase of  the Carriage and Blacksmith Workshops. Soon after, a construction project on the site commenced under the name of Carriageworks.\nThe vision for Carriageworks was to became an artistic hub. This hub would be a place where creative work could be explored, developed, commissioned and presented.\n\n###Ambiance: \nThe first thing you notice when you arrive is the size of these workshops. half a dozen shed has been scraped down and now offer vast empty space where exhibitions takes place. But Carriagework is not only a museum. It is a host of many activities from a farmer's market to a cafe and much more. A bit like the Ground of Alexandria. And because the place has been renovated following it's original material. You can really enjoy a nineteenth century industrial atmosphere.  \n\n\n\n\nCarriageworks. Contemporary multi-arts program that engages artists & audiences with ambitious, artist-led exhibitions & performances. View What's On.\nPlace is important to the practice of art.\n\nSpecialty roaster, The Little Marionette of Sydney’s Inner West, are  operating a pop up at Carriageworks offering a range of coffee, drinks  and snacks.\n Open daily, 9.30AM – 3PM\n\n\n### Collection: \nAdding to the rich cultural atmosphere at Carriageworks are a number  of Resident Organisations, all working within the contemporary arts  sector: Contemporary Asian Australian Performance (CAAP), Erth, Force  Majeure, Performance Space, Sydney Chamber Opera, Moogahlin, Felix Media  and Marrugeku.\nOne of the main adantage of Carriagework is the size of its room. Which allow for really ambitious art installation, which could not been hosted anywhere else.\n\n### Pricing: \n\n### Location:  \nopen 10am – 6pm daily and open until late on performance nights.\nFor more information view Carriageworks Artistic Program.\nRedfern Station | 8 minute walk\nCarriageworks is housed in the old Eveleigh Rail Yards at Wilson  Street, located within the emerging Redfern Waterloo precinct, and has  been developed by the NSW State Government through Arts NSW.\n\n[address]() \n[website](http://carriageworks.com.au)"
