            "header" : "article-header-5b31b21c54e7f415b7538e1b.jpeg",
            "short_content" : "Ju Mak is a secret Korean restaurant hidden in the center of Sydney CBD. Take the time to find its entrance, and you will be rewarded with a wide range of great Korean meals.",
            "title" : "Ju Mak",
            "content_html" : "<h3 id=\"ambiance\">Ambiance:</h3>\n<p>Ju Mak aim is to create a authentic Koran restaurant in the middle of the city. The restaurant is hidden in a side alleyway of George street. The place is really warm and cozy in comparison of street outside. This feeling is accrued by the wooden furniture and the yellow light. Furn fact, the lights are covered by some golden teapots for some obscure reason. The place is divided in 2 floors, both good, but the first foot feels more typical. But form a general stand point the food is more interesting than the interior design.</p>\n<h3 id=\"cuisine\">Cuisine:</h3>\n<p>The restaurant naturally carries a Korean tradition. Starting with Kimchi, a fermented vegetable that has been a staple of the Koran diet for generations. After this free starter, a large range of dishes are available. From vegetarian soup, to Korean fried chicken and Hotpots. Some meals are individuals when some other are for sharing. They can be cooked or come raw and cook in front of you. Follow your mood, all the dishes worth a try. Check out their <a href=\"http://cityjumak.com.au/menu/\" target=\"_blank\">menu</a> to see their full range of dishes. A small variety of drinks are also available, soft drinks, but also some Korean beer, and Soju. You can find pictures of their dishes on their <a href=\"http://cityjumak.com.au\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>. </p>\n<h3 id=\"pricing\">Pricing:</h3>\n<p>The prices vary from $10 for some chicken wings to somewhere around $50 for the most expensive dishes. Meal like fried rice, noodle and soup  have an average price of $15 which is acceptable for a filling meal in the CBD. Others, like hot pot are more expensive, starting at $40 but served 2 to 3 persons. The beers start at $6 for a can of Cass, and Soju is $10. The <a href=\"http://cityjumak.com.au/menu/\" target=\"_blank\">menu</a> as the extensive lists of pricing.</p>\n<h3 id=\"service\">Service:</h3>\n<p>The staff is welcoming and quite fast to pick up your order. With the free Starter, called Kimchi, you won't have to wait long before you can start eating something. And the waiting line isn't very long.</p>\n<h3 id=\"location\">Location:</h3>\n<p>The restaurant is 3 minutes walk from Town Hall station, but it is easily missed because of its location. It is situated in a dark alley adjacent of George street.  The alley is far from being dangerous, but you wouldn't think about a restaurant located there. To help you find which one it is, find the Metro Theater and follow its adjacent street for 50 meters. The alley is empty except for 2 - 3 Korean shop at the start of it. If you have any double check here is the <a href=\"https://www.google.com/maps/place/Jumak+Korean+Restaurant/@-33.8755707,151.2051599,17z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m5!3m4!1s0x6b12ae3dac965da9:0xc4db9d65cec22b89!8m2!3d-33.8755707!4d151.2073486\" target=\"_blank\">map</a>.  </p>",
            "content_markdown" : "### Ambiance:\nJu Mak aim is to create a authentic Koran restaurant in the middle of the city. The restaurant is hidden in a side alleyway of George street. The place is really warm and cozy in comparison of street outside. This feeling is accrued by the wooden furniture and the yellow light. Furn fact, the lights are covered by some golden teapots for some obscure reason. The place is divided in 2 floors, both good, but the first foot feels more typical. But form a general stand point the food is more interesting than the interior design.\n\n### Cuisine:\nThe restaurant naturally carries a Korean tradition. Starting with Kimchi, a fermented vegetable that has been a staple of the Koran diet for generations. After this free starter, a large range of dishes are available. From vegetarian soup, to Korean fried chicken and Hotpots. Some meals are individuals when some other are for sharing. They can be cooked or come raw and cook in front of you. Follow your mood, all the dishes worth a try. Check out their [menu](http://cityjumak.com.au/menu/) to see their full range of dishes. A small variety of drinks are also available, soft drinks, but also some Korean beer, and Soju. You can find pictures of their dishes on their [website](http://cityjumak.com.au). \n\n### Pricing: \nThe prices vary from $10 for some chicken wings to somewhere around $50 for the most expensive dishes. Meal like fried rice, noodle and soup  have an average price of $15 which is acceptable for a filling meal in the CBD. Others, like hot pot are more expensive, starting at $40 but served 2 to 3 persons. The beers start at $6 for a can of Cass, and Soju is $10. The [menu](http://cityjumak.com.au/menu/) as the extensive lists of pricing.\n\n### Service: \nThe staff is welcoming and quite fast to pick up your order. With the free Starter, called Kimchi, you won't have to wait long before you can start eating something. And the waiting line isn't very long.\n\n###Location: \nThe restaurant is 3 minutes walk from Town Hall station, but it is easily missed because of its location. It is situated in a dark alley adjacent of George street.  The alley is far from being dangerous, but you wouldn't think about a restaurant located there. To help you find which one it is, find the Metro Theater and follow its adjacent street for 50 meters. The alley is empty except for 2 - 3 Korean shop at the start of it. If you have any double check here is the [map](https://www.google.com/maps/place/Jumak+Korean+Restaurant/@-33.8755707,151.2051599,17z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m5!3m4!1s0x6b12ae3dac965da9:0xc4db9d65cec22b89!8m2!3d-33.8755707!4d151.2073486).  "
