            "header" : "article-header-5b3f4de0eee0b11f5e8b6e74.jpeg",
            "header_by_markdown" : "[@christopher__burns](https://unsplash.com/photos/x5tVBbQ3G-4) from Unsplash",
            "header_by_html" : "<p><a href=\"https://unsplash.com/photos/x5tVBbQ3G-4\" target=\"_blank\">@christopher__burns</a> from Unsplash</p>",
            "short_content" : "Mygov is the online platform to deal with every government services. From the taxation office to the unemployment benefit. But before accessing these services you will need to link them with your account.",
            "title" : "Create Mygov account",
            "content_html" : "<h3 id=\"wheretostart\">Where to start?</h3>\n<p>Creating a Mygov account is a pretty straight forward process. From their <a href=\"https://my.gov.au/\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>, click on register and fill up the following form. The only document required will be your <a href=\"/article/5b41fa93e3669e23cbbeffd4\" target=\"_blank\">TFN (Tax file number)</a>. It is probably laying under that pile of other documents you keep \"just in case\". The registration shouldn't very long. Once done, we recommend you to save somewhere your answers to the safety questions. MyGov will ask them after every login to confirm your identity. It is important to know than even the slightest mistake will be refused by the website.  If you want to avoid this, you can voluntarily add your phone number. In that case a code will be sent to you. From website dashboard you will be able to link a bunch a different services, including the ATO.</p>\n<h3 id=\"howtolinktheatoservice\">How to link the ATO service</h3>\n<p>Most of the services available on Mygov dashboard are exclusive to citizenship. But some of them, like the ATO, are also available to expatriates. To link the ATO, you will need to confirm your identity. 5 options will be given, but only 2 of them are necessary to confirm your identity. The first time I did struggle to pick the right option, some of them are easier than others. </p>\n<ul>\n<li>The easy one to start with is your payment summary. You got this paper from your employer somewhere during June before the tax season. This is also the document who will allow you to claim your tax back.</li>\n<li>The second one I ended up doing is your bank account details. Enter your BSB and account number and you should be fine.</li>\n</ul>\n<p></br>\nThe first time I was focusing on trying to link my superannuation. Which resulted in me searching for an account settled up by my bank few months earlier. And to be honest I am still unsure of their login details.</p>\n<h3 id=\"ineligibletolink\">Ineligible to link</h3>\n<p><img src=\"https://i.imgur.com/eifPL7w.png\" alt=\"Ineligible to link\" />\nIneligibility to link your MyGov account to the ATO is a common issue. Usually your company will create a profile for you on the ATO to fill their taxes. But it is not required, and if they don't do it the ATO has no information to check your identity against. In that case you will be required to call them at their number 13 28 61. They'll ask you to confirm you TFN and passport number before approving your request. That does not take more than 5 minutes.</p>\n<h3 id=\"whatnext\">What next?</h3>\n<p>Congratulation for settling up your account. There is not much else to do. If you did that for the tax back we have a following <a href=\"/article/5b2da4d4ae86ed7f92ac88e1\" target=\"_blank\">article</a> on the subject. You also will be happy to know than your TFN is also saved on your dashboard. It's also worth mentioning than Mygov is also a <a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/au/app/mygov-access-code-creator/id1305497801?mt=8\" target=\"_blank\">mobile app</a>. But with a rating of only 1.4/5 (July 2018) and a lots of bugs, we do not recommend it. eg:</p>\n<p></br>\n<img src=\"https://i.imgur.com/sR04Hdv.png\" alt=\"apple review\" /></p>",
            "content_markdown" : "### Where to start?\nCreating a Mygov account is a pretty straight forward process. From their [website](https://my.gov.au/), click on register and fill up the following form. The only document required will be your [TFN (Tax file number)](/article/5b41fa93e3669e23cbbeffd4). It is probably laying under that pile of other documents you keep \"just in case\". The registration shouldn't very long. Once done, we recommend you to save somewhere your answers to the safety questions. MyGov will ask them after every login to confirm your identity. It is important to know than even the slightest mistake will be refused by the website.  If you want to avoid this, you can voluntarily add your phone number. In that case a code will be sent to you. From website dashboard you will be able to link a bunch a different services, including the ATO.\n\n### How to link the ATO service\nMost of the services available on Mygov dashboard are exclusive to citizenship. But some of them, like the ATO, are also available to expatriates. To link the ATO, you will need to confirm your identity. 5 options will be given, but only 2 of them are necessary to confirm your identity. The first time I did struggle to pick the right option, some of them are easier than others. \n  - The easy one to start with is your payment summary. You got this paper from your employer somewhere during June before the tax season. This is also the document who will allow you to claim your tax back.\n  - The second one I ended up doing is your bank account details. Enter your BSB and account number and you should be fine.\n\n</br>\nThe first time I was focusing on trying to link my superannuation. Which resulted in me searching for an account settled up by my bank few months earlier. And to be honest I am still unsure of their login details.\n\n### Ineligible to link\n![Ineligible to link](https://i.imgur.com/eifPL7w.png)\nIneligibility to link your MyGov account to the ATO is a common issue. Usually your company will create a profile for you on the ATO to fill their taxes. But it is not required, and if they don't do it the ATO has no information to check your identity against. In that case you will be required to call them at their number 13 28 61. They'll ask you to confirm you TFN and passport number before approving your request. That does not take more than 5 minutes.\n\n### What next?\nCongratulation for settling up your account. There is not much else to do. If you did that for the tax back we have a following [article](/article/5b2da4d4ae86ed7f92ac88e1) on the subject. You also will be happy to know than your TFN is also saved on your dashboard. It's also worth mentioning than Mygov is also a [mobile app](https://itunes.apple.com/au/app/mygov-access-code-creator/id1305497801?mt=8). But with a rating of only 1.4/5 (July 2018) and a lots of bugs, we do not recommend it. eg:\n\n</br>\n![apple review](https://i.imgur.com/sR04Hdv.png)"
